litical control while representing the claims of religion in brick, wood, and stone. The architectural vocabulary of the Soviet state celebrated industrialization, mechanization, and communal life. Buildings and landscapes have expressed utopian urges as well as lofty spiritual goals. Country houses and memorials have encoded their own messages. In Architectures of Russian Identity, James Cracraft and Daniel Rowland gather a group of authors from a wide variety of backgrounds—including history and architectural history, linguistics, literary studies, geography, and political science—to survey the political and symbolic meanings of many different kinds of structures. Fourteen heavily illustrated chapters demonstrate the remarkable fertility of the theme of architecture, broadly defined, for a range of fields dealing with Russia and its surrounding territories. The authors engage key terms in contemporary historiography—identity, nationality, visual culture—and assess the applications of each in Russian contexts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aArchitecturezRussia (Federation). 0aArchitecture, Modern. 4aArchitecture & Preservation. 4aArt History. 7aARCHITECTURE / History / General.2bisacsh1 aBassin, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCastillo, Greg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCracraft, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCracraft, James, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCrews, Robert D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDay, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEly, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlier, Michael S., econtributor.4ctb4https:/